  {
    "id": 1621359391868,
    "type": "text",
    "content": "\"<h1>Condition</h1>\""
  },
  {
    "id": 1636662065710,
    "type": "grid",
    "content": [
      [
        {
          "id": 1636662074274,
          "type": "text",
          "content": "\"<h2>Live Hard Coral Cover</h2><p><span style=\\\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\\\">The trend of live hard coral cover follows a dramatic pattern, with coral bleaching being the major driver of coral loss in the South Asia region.&nbsp;Average values for the region are dominated by&nbsp;the&nbsp;Maldive&nbsp;and&nbsp;Chagos&nbsp;archipelagos, which include three-quarters of reefs&nbsp;across&nbsp;the region.&nbsp;Monitoring was limited prior to 1998, but available data suggest coral cover averaged between 38% and 45%.&nbsp;The mass coral bleaching event in 1998 resulted in a loss of 70% of&nbsp;that coral cover&nbsp;(to 12%), but this was followed by significant recovery (by 2010), particularly in&nbsp;Chagos&nbsp;and the Maldives where local threats are low. A second major bleaching event in 2016 and localized coral bleaching events from 2017-2019 have continued to cause declines in live hard coral cover – to under 25%.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\""
        }
      ],
      [
        {
          "id": 1636662077004,
          "type": "text",
          "content": "\"<h2>Algae Cover</h2><p><span style=\\\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\\\">The average cover of algae across South Asia was relatively low and stable at about 10% until 2008, after which there was a progressive increase to 14% by 2018.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\""
        }
      ]
    ]
  },
